# SplitCents TODO

## Project direction
- Keep the initial focus on a standalone personal budgeting app for solo users.
- Treat shared or collaborative features as a later phase rather than part of the MVP.

## MVP scope
- Define and lock the MVP around income tracking, recurring bills, budget planning, savings goals, and a simple monthly overview.
- Keep bill frequencies simple at first: monthly by default, with support for weekly and annual bills.
- Prioritize a clean, usable workflow over advanced forecasting or bank integrations.

## Implementation backlog
- [ ] Finalize the MVP scope and success criteria.
- [ ] Set up the solution structure and baseline architecture for API, core, and infrastructure layers.
- [ ] Implement user registration, authentication, and basic user management.
- [ ] Add income entry and recurring bill management.
- [ ] Add budget categories and monthly planning features.
- [ ] Add savings goals and progress tracking.
- [ ] Build the dashboard/summary experience and basic reminders.
- [ ] Add testing, validation, and release preparation.

## Planning and project management
- [ ] Choose and set up appropriate planning/project management software (for example Jira, Azure DevOps, Trello, Linear, or Notion).
- [ ] Create a backlog, sprint board, and workflow columns for backlog, planned, in progress, review, and done.
- [ ] Break the MVP into manageable tickets and assign priorities.

## Notes
- Use the implementation plan and capability documents as the main source of truth for scope and priorities.
- Revisit the roadmap after the MVP is released to decide whether to add sharing, forecasting, or account integrations.

